Reading Data Into SAS

Data with Prespecified Column Spacing
(No Within-Subject Delimiter)

Dataset with Prespecified Spacing

Here, you are given a text file with a continuous stream of numbers with no variable label and no delimiter (e.g.tab, comma, etc). Each row corresponds to individual observation and any white space implies missing data.

If you are given a dataset similar to the text file above, you should be given a coding sheet with data descriptors such as variable names and their designated column numbers.

Here, the sheet tells you that sex is in column 1 (where 1 = Male, 2 = Female) while age is in columns 2-3.

Step by Step Guide: Loading Sex, Age (Part I)

Below is the general structure to create a SAS data. I am choosing to call it nhis_data.

data nhis_data; 
  {to be filled}
run;

The infile statement I created tells SAS the path where the data is located.

data nhis_data; 
  infile "\\Client\H$\Documents\Regression_Analysis\nhis_data.txt";
  {to be filled}
run;

Step by Step Guide: Loading Sex, Age (Part II)

Next, I am telling SAS to create a sex variable. Here, I am specifying to treat column 1 as the entries for the sex variable.

data nhis_data; 
  infile "\\Client\H$\Documents\Regression_Analysis\nhis_data.txt";
  input sex 1 {to be filled}; 
run;

Finally, according to the coding scheme presented earlier, age is located in columns 2-3. The finalized code below tells SAS to create a nhis_data dataset, find the relevant file using the infile statement, and create both sex and age variables that are located in columns 1 and 2-3, respectively.

data nhis_data; 
  infile "\\Client\H$\Documents\Regression_Analysis\nhis_data.txt";
  input sex 1 age 2-3;
run;

Verification

We may use proc print to verify our work:

proc print data=nhis_data (obs=5);
run;

Output:

Mutating the Data

Suppose you want to the accomplish the following task: change the 1-2 coding of gender to their categorical names (F for female, M for male); and create a categorical age variable where individuals are labeled AgeCat1 when below 30, AgeCat2 when 30 to below 60, and AgeCat3 when 60 or older.

Heres one way to accomplish both:

data nhis_data_v2;
    infile "\\Client\H$\Documents\Regression_Analysis\ReadingSAS\nhis_data.txt";
    input sex 1 age 2-3;
    
    if sex = 1 then sex_v2 = "M";
    else sex_v2 = "F";
    
    if 0 <= age < 30 then age_v2 = "AgeCat1";
    else if 30 <= age < 60 then age_v2 = "AgeCat2";
    else age_v2 = "AgeCat3";
run;

Verification

We may use proc print to verify our work:

proc print data=nhis_data_v2 (obs=5);
run;
